<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>THE HOME AFFAIRS SELECT COMMITTEE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#d9d9d9; font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Matthew Ellis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Police and Crime Commissioner for Staffordshire [PCC Progress 37]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 56.7pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 56.7pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">AN OVERVIEW OF </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">THE EFFECTIVENESS OF COMMISSIONERS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">IN:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">REDUCING CRIME AND DELIVERING AN EFFECTIVE POLICE SERVICE WITHIN THEIR POLICE FORCE AREA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">PROMOTING LOCAL POLICING PRIORITIES; AND</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> ESTABLISHING COLLABORATIONS AGREEMENTS WITH OTHER COMMISSIONERS, POLICING ORGANISATIONS AND PARTNERS</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is too early to make definitive assertions on the overall effectiveness or otherwise of PCCs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">41 different elected individuals with varying capacities, experience and nous means it is only possible currently to understand the evolving potential and effectiveness of the PCC role. It is important to separate the performance of individual PCCs from assessing the effectiveness, real or potential, of the new role itself. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is clear to me that those PCCs with relevant experience, for instance ex MPs, top tier local authority exec members or people with understanding of large complex organisations have found their feet faster than those who were elected because they simply ‘aren’t a politician’. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some PCCs are struggling to varying degrees but there are probably 20 who are making the positive difference envisaged for the sector, locally and nationally, and for their constituents.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In my view, comparisons between the PCC role and the Police Authorities it replaced have been unhelpful. The PCC role bears some of the responsibilities of the old PA but any sense of a like for like switch dumbs down the wider opportunities the new position provides. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bringing partners together and driving positive reform to what is a relatively insular sector defines the scale of difference.  The individual accountability of decision making and proven public recognition of the role which is ten times greater than that of the PA in less than a year is also defining. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It’s clear that the relationship between the old PA and Police was sometimes verging on sycophantic rather than challenging. Evidence from any of the few staff who remain with the new office from the ‘old world’ would be insightful. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When it comes to pace, proactivity, culture, public awareness and public interaction what one said is telling…</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:18.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When it comes to pace, proactivity, culture, public awareness and public interaction what one said is telling…</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Looking back at this time last year things were literally ‘plodding along’. That was until the start of the Police and Crime Commissioner.  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Within weeks the new attitude and mind-set started to open up this familiar yet highly insular environment.  A new energy combined with business logic started to soon emerge and now there is never a dull moment. As part of a team of people with a shared vision, free from the shackles of rank and obedience we’ve helped create a new dynamic culture where we influence decisions and we can make things happen. It feels like previously strangulated talent has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">unleashed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> - how great is that feeling at end of the day!</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In my opinion the PCC role has enormous potential to act as an ‘honest broker’… to bring disparate services together towards common goals and outcomes. It is unquestionably the best opportunity so far to break down organisational barriers in community safety, policing and engendering closer integration of the wider sector to achieve defined outcomes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It has also challenged head on the ‘police to police only’ culture which hinders efforts to join up services in order to reduce future demand by investing in preventative solutions outside the policing realm. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Staffordshire I’ve intentionally ensured appropriate distanced between the PCC role and the police. Instead I adopt that honest broker approach while rigorously carrying out the governance responsibilities transferred from the old PA. However, I always talk in public about ‘the police’ or ‘they’ rather than ‘we’ in order to be seen clearly by all agencies as even handed and not part of the police organisation. It greatly enhances the joint working environment.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That role of breaking down silo thinking in the wider sector is critical to progress. Different public bodies work in isolation. Too often, a service provider will change or cut services to save itself £1million but by doing so inadvertently shifts perhaps £10million brand new costs to the wider sector. That scenario is prevalent and a race to the bottom when it comes to sustainability and reducing demand for future services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The new Safer Staffordshire Board I’ve established brings together the Local Criminal Justice Board (LCJB) with other agencies including local authorities. It not only stimulates broader relationships and new opportunities for joint working but the honest broker role allows free-flowing and greater cross cutting challenge. There are claims that constructive challenge in the previous governance and collaboration environment has been limited because of agencies fearing a larger challenge being returned by another for casting the first. The honest broker approach of the PCC role counters that. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Efficiency savings secured from PCC budgets have also provided the opportunity for me to create an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Incentivisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Fund of £2million that is governed through that new Board. It is there to fund short term double running costs in order to stimulate service improvement for the long term. Lack of defined change funding is often the reason for not making services work more effectively for the long haul. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are also launching innovation challenges at every level from the ‘shop floor’ to the ‘board room’. I believe those who work at the sharp end often bring more innovative and practical reforms as they do the job every day. You don’t have to be a Superintendent or above to have a good idea! </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The positives that have been proved, almost across the board, is a reinvigoration in engagement between police governance and local people and the ability of PCCs to bring to the top of the national agenda those issues which the public believe are important but had failed to receive the focus they should. I refer to the work in Staffordshire to profile and stimulate action on mental health incidents in policing (The Staffordshire Report on Policing &amp; Mental Health).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Staffordshire the number of people I have engaged with face to face has recently exceeded 12,000 since January 2013 with correspondence to the PCC office averaging 40 times more each week than to the old Police Authority, and growing.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The Police &amp; Crime Plane, Safer Fairer United Communities, received the biggest number of responses to any public consultation in Staffordshire other than the Stafford Hospital one which was marginally more.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Any democratic process will result in differences, positive and negative across different areas or constituencies but in this case the opportunities emerging from this new role are clear. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">TRANSPARENCY &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">THE ROLE OF COMMISSIONERS IN HOLDING THEIR CHIEF CONSTABLES TO ACCOUNT</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Positive steps are being made to provide better and more open accountability of the Chief Constable.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is my view that p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ublic confidence in the police not only depends upon Police Officers demonstrating the highest level of personal and professional standards of behaviour, but in the integrity of a fair </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and just complaints system.  I am of the opinion that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public have the right to expect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">police services to protect them, not only in upholding the law but by providing an appropriate service when an officer or staff member fails to behave w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ith integrity, proportionately, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and professionalism.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Recent events have diminished public confidence in the way complaints against the police are managed.  The publication of the raw, unedited version of the Port Vale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Report</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> represented only the first step on a positive journey, as it is my view that the perception of internal investigations will only alter when we open our doors to the public to champion a new era of transparency.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Port Vale R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eview provides a prime example of my </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">drive and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with regards to transparency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and ambition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to improve and maintain public confidence.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This new era, is in my view, marked by establishing an Independent Public Scrutiny Panel.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By opening up to the public, a dip-s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ample selection of complaints Staffordshire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would lead the way in achieving full and open public accountability.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Through engagement and education, members of the public will be given a platform to scrutinise and challenge the complaints procedure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and in turn we would be given an opportunity to repair and restore confidence in the integrity and fairness of our internal investigations.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is my view that the panel’s key functions would be to review, scrutinise and most significantly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">processes used are appropriate and that any outcome is accurate, honest and justified.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In order to restore public confidence we not only need to engage with communities, but provide as much tangible evidence to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> prove the legitimacy and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">integrity of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">work and services as a whole.  We must remember that the minimum statutory requirements for publication o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nly provide a minimum threshold and it is my intention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to go above and beyond that threshold.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, open and public accountability is only one step on a much bigger journey on which I intend to restore and revive public confidence.  It is my view, and I trust it is the opinion of all other Police and Crime Commissioners, that transparency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and accountability in all areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is paramount in proving the integrity and successfulness of any kind of work.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">THE ROLE OF POLICE AND CRIME PANELS IN HOLDING THEIR COMMISSIONERS TO ACCOUNT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst I am taking positive steps on a journey which will see the Chief Constable held accountable by an independent public scrutiny panel, it is the role of the Police and Crime Panel to hold me to account.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Staffordshire and Stoke-on-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Trent Police and Crime Panel first came into being on the 30th July 2012.  It is made up of an elected member from each of the ten local au</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thorities in Staffordshire and Stoke-on-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Trent plus two independent members, and is chaired by County Councillor Frank Chapman. Its role is to prov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ide constructive scrutiny of my</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and to hold me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to account.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To date,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Police and Crime Panel have met to look at a range of key issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including to consideration of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the draft Police and Crime Plan, particularly the most recent iteration which is a radical departure from the tradition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">al form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Panel were supportive of my</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 4 priorities as se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t out in the draft Plan but mad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e some suggestions about additional information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requested greater detail in certain areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Additionally the Police and Crime Panel have met to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> scrutinise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">draft budget and precept for 2013/14</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o hold confirmatory hearings for the Deputy Police and Crime Commissioner, the Chief of Staff and the Chief Financial Officer.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the course of their meetings the Panel have also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> questioned and scrutinised me on my</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> approach on a variety of issues including:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The introduction of “Straight Talk” sessions with police officers.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 73.7pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Proposals for IT improvements intended to free up officers time and provide real time information. Officers will have remote access to information whilst on patrol removing need to return to the station</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The new Staffordshire Police Cadet Scheme, including how it is funded, how it recruits across ethnic groups, and how it trains its cadets. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The abandonment of Regulation A19 compulsory retirement of police officers.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Police performance and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">my stated ambition to introduce more meaningful measurement systems and to move away from a target chasing culture. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Panel have confirmed that as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they have found that I am “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">very willing to enter into a dialogue with them, and ready to accept their challenge and constructive scrutiny, and the Panel looking forward to the relationship continuing in this positive vein</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">THE DIVISION OF FUNCTIONS AND STAFF BETWEEN COMMISSIONER AND CHIEF CONSTABLES FOLLOWING THE SATGE 2 TRANSFERS UNDER THE POLICE REFORM AND SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY ACT 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Staffordshire, most of the staff currently employed by the PCC will transfer to the Chief Constable i.e. the ‘maximum transfer’ route</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In total, there are 1527 individuals that may be impacted on by the Stage 2 transfer proposals and of these: - </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">18 (17 people plus 1 vacancy) posts wil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l remain in the emplo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the PCC after April 2014; </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7 posts transfer to the employment of Staffordshire County Council;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1503 posts transfer to the employ of the Chief Constable; of these however, 146 may transfer to alternative arrangements as a result of current or forthcoming reviews or opportunities that may impact on employment arrangements.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The staffing proposals are too supplemented by a Service Level Agreement and Memorandum of Understanding that set out how the proposed division of functions will work practically, including my access to those that work for the Chief Constable, the management of contracts and assets and the governance arrangements that support our working arrangements.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I know that some of my PCC colleagues have taken the view that Stage 2 is bureaucratic fiddling and that what worked for Police Authorities could continue to work for PCCs. I think however, that there is a danger in this approach that being not recognizing the very different role that the PCC can potentially play in an area such as Staffordshire which has 2 top tier local authorities, 8 district / borough local authorities, 6 clinical commissioning groups, a criminal justice sector that works primarily on a broader Midlands footprint and with this, complex community safety governance arrangements. Whilst I will meet my statutory requirements in holding the Chief Constable to account and need an office that assists me in doing this, it is also the case that I together with the Chief Constable can engage better with local people / communities, pull partners together, broker change and shape the broader safety agenda. In doing so, the Stage 2 division of functions helps to clarify how these ambitions might be achieved and sets out how two pan-Staffordshire functions will work together and with partners to ensure that policing delivers and community safety improves.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I believe that basing a Stage 2 proposal on sound rationale provides the best chance of success. My approach has been based on a number of principles and an analysis of local factors, both of which have assisted in reaching a proposal: -</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A need for clarity of role between my office and that of the Force/  partners;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My electoral mandate best being discharged through the model of being a commissioner of services;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Chief Constable and the operational elements of the Force must remain operationally independent and be seen as a provider of services;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My work with the Police (and other partners) must be a joint endeavor to  improve outcomes for local people as set out in my Safer, Fairer United Communities strategy;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A need for effective arrangements, which best support the Chief Constable and I to carry out our statutory roles;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Creating a ‘fit for purpose’ organizational structure that is ‘future-proofed’;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A need to secure value for money.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Delivering a structural solution that meets the underlying principles is also dependent on the particular arrangements that exist in an area. In Staffordshire, the issues highlighted in reaching the proposal included the following:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My strategic vision that is focused on developing partnership and collaborative working to deliver across a broader community safety agenda;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The localism agenda that focuses on local commissioners having the capability and freedom to deliver local solutions – I do not intend to be prescriptive in how local problems are solved, but want to know that they are being addressed;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The intent for a ‘one Staffordshire’ approach reflected in the willingness of all key public sector partners to work together. This has a particular relevance to developing single approaches and solutions that are more effective and efficient than present arrangements; </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The good working relationship that I and my office have with the Chief Constable that will result in effective governance to oversee progress in the short, medium and long-term;</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 52pt; padding-left:20pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My view that my office remains lean, focusing on strategy, delivery of opportunities, change management and governance and that the Chief Constable is able to focus on delivering effective and efficient policing.   </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">THE ROLE OF COMMISSIONERS IN BUDGET AND PRECEPT SETTING</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Establishing the annual budget and local precept are key requirements placed on Police and Crime Commissioners. My view is that decisions such as these require me to be well-informed, cognisant of the facts and the views of the Chief Constable, partners and local people and communities. Having been in post for a year, I think that I understand well what the different views of stakeholders are and importantly what those mean for budget setting; like many of my PCC colleagues I have put major effort into engaging with the Police (at all levels), partners, communities and local people. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst policing services are the major beneficiary of budget setting, I have also to ensure that community safety and related functions are funded to meet needs; my strategy sets out my commitment to partnership, whole-system working and local delivery. The role of the PCC is often to broker arrangements between all of those involved in delivering improved community safety and that means that it is essential to reflect this in budget and precept setting.       </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My view naturally leads to an approach that is focused on efficiency, effectiveness and whole-system change rather than ‘salami slicing’; for me, the total funding available to the public sector as oppose to the budget that I am responsible for offers the opportunities looking forwards and that is one of the reasons why I have not increased the precept in 2012/13 and do not intend to do so in 2013/14. I believe that through working with partners and incentivising efficient and effective approaches, the current funding available can be made to work harder and improve outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:12.01pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My background as the Cabinet Member for Adult Social Care at Staffordshire County Council has provided me with hugely valuable experience in managing budget and precept issues. I recognise that not all PCCs have this background and that therefore, the role of Police and Crime Panels in reviewing budget and precept proposals adds significant value.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Matthew Ellis</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Police and Crime Commissioner for Staffordshire</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><h4 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center; text-indent:-27pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GENERAL NOTICE OF REGISTRABLE INTERESTS</span></h4><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">I, </span><span style="font-family:'Comic Sans MS'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Matthew Ellis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Police and Crime Commissioner for Staffordshire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> give notice that</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">I have set out below under the appropriate headings my interests which I am required to declare.  I have put “none” where I have no such interests under any heading. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">I recognise that it can be a criminal offence to:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">) omit the information which ought to be given in this notice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">(ii) provide information which is materially false or misleading;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">(iii) fail to give further notices in order to:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 43.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">- bring up to date information given in this notice</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 43.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">             </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">- declare an interest which I acquire after the date of this notice and have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">               </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">declare.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this document:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“body in which the relevant person has a beneficial interest” means a firm in which the relevant person is a partner or a body corporate of which the relevant person is a director, or in the securities of which the relevant person has a beneficial interest;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“director” includes a member of the committee of management of an industrial and provident society;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“land” includes an easement, servitude, interest or right in or over land which does not carry with it a right for the relevant person (alone or jointly with another) to occupy the land or to receive income;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “elected local policing body” means the elected Local Policing Body to which the relevant person has been elected.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“relevant period” means the period of 12 months ending with the day on which the relevant person makes an entry amendment or deletion to the register of disclosable interests.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“relevant person” means the person(s) who is/are elected/appointed Police and Crime Commissioner and Deputy Police and Crime Commissioner.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“securities” means shares, debentures, debenture stock, loan stock, bonds, units of a collective investment scheme within the meaning of the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000(b) and other securities of any description, other than money deposited with a building society.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 21.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">1.  Employment, office, trade, profession or vocation</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Disclosable interest:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Any employment, office, trade, profession or vocation carried on for profit or gain.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Comic Sans MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">County Councillor for Lichfield Rural East (until April 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Comic Sans MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Comic Sans MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Owner of properties outside Staffs Border for re